## What Actually Clicked for Me

The insight that clarified the monitoring plan today is the difference between monitoring as detection and monitoring as assurance.

Monitoring as detection asks: has something gone wrong? GuardDuty, CloudTrail alerts, Config NON_COMPLIANT notifications — these are detection mechanisms. They fire when a security-relevant event occurs. They are reactive: the event happens, the alert fires, the ISSO investigates.

Monitoring as assurance asks: is the control still working as designed? The quarterly access review, the quarterly backup restoration test, the semi-annual audit log completeness test, the CP-3 retention check — these are assurance mechanisms. They run on a schedule regardless of whether any alerting has fired. They are proactive: the ISSO periodically verifies that the controls are effective, rather than waiting for a failure to reveal a degraded control.

The AU-12 finding from Day 79 is the most important illustration of why assurance monitoring matters. AWS Config was monitoring for CloudTrail enablement, log encryption, and tamper detection — detection mechanisms that were all functioning correctly. None of the detection mechanisms caught the fact that denied access events were not being captured by the OpenMRS audit log module. The gap was found through a proactive assurance test — the ISSO manually tested whether a denied access attempt generated an audit log entry. It did not.

A monitoring program built entirely on detection mechanisms would not have found this gap. The assurance mechanisms in the monitoring schedule are what found it. This is why the monitoring calendar must include both.

