## Audit Readiness — The Evidence Trail Principle

Audit readiness is not a sprint that happens two weeks before an audit. It is the continuous practice of producing evidence as a byproduct of normal security operations.

Every item in the monitoring calendar above produces evidence. The quarterly access review produces a signed review form. The backup restoration test produces a test record with timestamp and RTO. The audit log completeness test produces a pass/fail record per event type. The phishing simulation produces an aggregate click rate report. The monthly CloudTrail review produces a written summary.

This evidence trail means that when an OCR auditor or formal re-authorization assessor asks "how do you know your access controls are working?" the answer is not "we have a policy" — it is "here are four quarterly access review records, here is the M-004 finding that identified one over-privilege instance and the 24-hour correction timeline, and here is the SSP v1.2 update that added the HR notification requirement to prevent recurrence."

The Day 80 pre-audit narrative consistency check applies here: two weeks before any formal assessment, the ISSO reviews the monitoring log, POA&M, SSP, and assessment findings to confirm that the narrative is consistent — that the SSP describes what the monitoring program actually found, and that the POA&M accurately reflects the current status of all open items. Any inconsistency between the documentation layers is a finding waiting to be discovered by an assessor; it is far better to find and resolve it proactively.

**What audit readiness is not:** A clean dashboard with all green indicators. The Day 79 and Day 80 discussion of honest compliance mapping is directly relevant here. The AU-12 finding is in the monitoring log. The CP-2 AT RISK status is in the POA&M. The phishing simulation gap is in the metrics dashboard. An auditor who finds these items documented with honest status is looking at a mature monitoring program. An auditor who finds these items missing from the documentation and discovers them independently is looking at a program that was not audit-ready.

