## A Real-World Example That Made This Click

The value of assurance monitoring over detection-only monitoring is validated by the **2020 SolarWinds Orion supply chain compromise**, discussed briefly in Day 77.

The SolarWinds attackers operated within the target environments for months before detection. They used legitimate credentials, generated traffic that blended with normal network patterns, and specifically evaded detection mechanisms. The organizations that were compromised had extensive detection monitoring infrastructure — and the detection mechanisms did not fire because the attackers were operating through normal-looking access paths.

What the SolarWinds case validates for the OpenMRS monitoring program is that detection mechanisms alone are not sufficient. The semi-annual audit log completeness test is an assurance mechanism — it tests whether the audit trail would capture a specific attacker behavior (unauthorized access attempt), not whether any alerts are currently firing. If the test finds that unauthorized access attempts are not being logged (as the Day 79 test found for denied access events), the organization knows its forensic capability is limited before an incident exploits that limitation.

Detection monitoring tells you when something bad has happened. Assurance monitoring tells you whether your controls would detect something bad if it happened. Both are necessary. The OpenMRS monitoring program explicitly includes both.

